revision.text:
{{refimprove|date=March 2016}} An '''association copy''' is a term used to describe a copy of a [[book]] which once belonged to the author or someone connected with the author. It can also apply to a copy that once belonged to someone particularly associated with its contents.<ref name=":0" /> An association copy is often also a [[presentation copy]], in which the author gives the book to a friend, [[colleague]], notable person, or someone upon whom a [[Fictional character|character]] in the book is thought or known to have been based.
Association copies are highly [[collectable]].
An example of an association copy is Herman Melville's copy of ''The Narrative of the Most Extraordinary and Distressing Shipwreck of the Whaleship Essex of Nantucket'' that contains 18 pages of Melville's notes.<ref name=":0">{{Cite book | title = ABC For Book Collectors | last = Carter | first = John | last2 = Barker | first2 = Nicholas | publisher = Oak Knoll Books | year = 2010 | isbn = 9781584561125 | location = New Castle, DE | pages = 27 }}</ref>
