[[File:Bosniangraves bosniska gravar februari 2007 stecak stecci3.jpg|thumb|upright=1.15|Stećak in [[Radimlja]] necropolis]]
'''Stećak''' ({{Cyrl|Стећак|sr}}, {{IPA-sh|stetɕak|}}; plural: '''Stećci''', Стећци, {{IPA-sh|stetɕtsi|}}) is the name for monumental [[medieval]] [[tombstone]]s that lie scattered across [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]], and the border parts of [[Croatia]], [[Montenegro]] and [[Serbia]]. An estimated 60,000 are found within the borders of modern Bosnia and Herzegovina and the rest of 10,000 are found in what are today Croatia (4,400), Montenegro (3,500), and Serbia (2,100), at more than 3,300 odd sites with over 90% in poor condition.<ref name="Unesco">{{cite web |url=http://www.unesco.org/new/en/venice/about-this-office/single-view/news/joint_nomination_for_inclusion_of_stecci_medieval_tombstones_in_the_world_heritage_list#.Vv3BqvmLTIU |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160414002411/http://www.unesco.org/new/en/venice/about-this-office/single-view/news/joint_nomination_for_inclusion_of_stecci_medieval_tombstones_in_the_world_heritage_list |title=Joint Nomination for Inclusion of Stećci - Medieval Tombstones in the World Heritage List |publisher=[[UNESCO]] |date=14 April 2014 |archive-date=14 April 2016}}</ref><ref name="DW">{{cite news |last=Musli |first=Emir |title=Čiji su naši stećci? |url=http://www.dw.com/bs/%C4%8Diji-su-na%C5%A1i-ste%C4%87ci/a-18078579 |date=23 November 2014 |publisher=[[Deutsche Welle]] |language=Bosnian |access-date=1 April 2016}}</ref>

Appearing in the mid 12th century, with the first phase in the 13th century, the tombstones reached their peak in the 14th and 15th century, before disappearing during the [[Ottoman occupation of Bosnia and Herzegovina|Ottoman occupation]] in the very early 16th century.<ref name="Unesco"/> They were a common tradition amongst [[Bosnian Church|Bosnian]], [[Catholic Church|Catholic]] and [[Eastern Orthodox Church|Orthodox]] Church followers alike,<ref name="WM">{{cite web |last=Walasek |first=Helen |title=Marian Wenzel 18 December 1932 - 6 January 2002 |url=http://www.bosnia.org.uk/bosrep/report_format.cfm?articleid=874&reportid=153 |publisher=Bosnian Institute |year=2002}}</ref> and are often related to the autochthonous [[Vlachs in medieval Bosnia and Herzegovina|Vlach]] population,{{sfn|Lovrenović|2013|p=52, 72, 176, 307}} however the original ethnic and religious affiliation is still undetermined.{{sfn|Trako|2011|p=71–72, 73–74}} The [[epitaph]]s on them are mostly written in extinct [[Bosnian Cyrillic]] alphabet. The one of largest collection of these tombstones is named [[Radimlja]], west of [[Stolac]] in Bosnia and Herzegovina.<ref name="DW"/>

Stećci were inscribed as a [[UNESCO World Heritage Site]] in 2016. It includes a selection of 4,000 stećci at 28 necropolises – of which 22 from Bosnia and Herzegovina, two from Croatia, three from Montenegro, and three from Serbia.<ref name="Unesco2016">{{cite web |url=http://whc.unesco.org/en/decisions/6802 |title=Examination of nominations of cultural properties to the World Heritage List |publisher=[[UNESCO]] |date=2016 |access-date=20 March 2017}}</ref>

==Etymology==
The word itself is a [[Contraction (grammar)|contracted form]] of the older word *''stojećak'', which is derived from the [[South Slavic languages|South Slavic]] verb ''stajati'' (engl. ''stand'').{{sfn|Kužić|1999|p=176}} It literally means the "tall, standing thing".{{sfn|Buturovic|2016|p=114}} In Herzegovina they are also called as ''mašeti'' / ''mašete'' (Italian ''massetto'' meaning "big rock", or Turkish ''meşhet''/''mešhed'' meaning "tombstone of a fallen hero"{{refn|group="nb"|Turkish word ''meşhed'' means a monument erected to Islamic dead martyr ''şehid''. The issue with the derivation is that stećci are attributed to, for Islam, [[infidel]] Christians and Bogomils, term ''mašet'' can also be derived from Turkish ''maşatlik'' meaning "non-Muslim cemetery", term ''mašet'' is of male while ''mašeta'' is of female gender, which is specific for Muslims.{{sfn|Trako|2011|p=72}}}}), in Central and Western Bosnia as ''mramori'' / ''mramorje'' / ''mramorovi'' (marble), while in Serbia and Montenegro as ''usađenik'' (implantation). On the stećci inscriptions they are called as ''bilig'' (mark), ''kamen bilig'' (stone mark), ''kâm'' / ''kami'' / ''kamen'' (stone), ''hram'' (shrine), ''zlamen'' (sign), ''kuća'' (house), ''raka'' (pit), ''greb/grob'' (grave).{{sfn|Trako|2011|p=72}}{{sfn|Buturovic|2016|p=114}}{{sfn|Lovrenović|2013|p=59–60}}<ref name="UnescoBiH">{{cite web |url=http://whc.unesco.org/en/tentativelists/5607 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160820104920/http://whc.unesco.org/en/tentativelists/5607/ |title=Stećaks - Mediaeval Tombstones (Bosnia and Herzegovina) |date=18 April 2011 |archive-date=20 August 2016 |publisher=UNESCO |access-date=1 April 2016}}</ref> In 1495 lectionary they are recorded as ''kamy'' (stone).{{sfn|Kužić|2001|p=272}}{{sfn|Bulog|2007|p=390}}

Although under the name ''stećak'' is meant high monolithic standing stones (i.e. ''sanduk'' and ''sljemenjak'' form), in the 20th century the word ''stećak'' was accepted in science as general term, including for plate tombstones (i.e. ''ploče'').{{sfn|Kužić|1999|p=176}}{{sfn|Mužić|2009|p=322}} The original reference to the word ''stećak'' itself is uncertain and seems to be modern invention as it can only be traced from the note by [[Ivan Kukuljević Sakcinski]] from 1851,{{sfn|Kužić|2001|p=269}} dictionary by [[Vuk Karadžić]] from 1852 (in the first edition from 1812 the term did not exist), although he contradicted himself as the commoners from [[Zagvozd]] called them ''starovirsko'' ("of the old faith"),{{sfn|Kužić|2001|p=268}} dictionary by [[Bogoslav Šulek]] from 1860 and so on,{{sfn|Kužić|2001|p=270}} while academic dictionaries mention it only from 1956/58.{{sfn|Kužić|2001|p=267}} It is considered that the term was usually used in [[East Herzegovina]] and in the area of [[Raška (region)|Stari Vlah]] in Serbia.{{sfn|Kužić|2001|p=268}} Until the very early 20th century there was wandering in terminology, and some scholars proposed general terms like ''nadgrobni biljezi'' (gravestone markers) and ''mramorje'' (marble) to be more appropriate.{{sfn|Kužić|1999|p=176}}

The term ''stećak'' is uncommon in regional dialects and without [[Etiology|etiological]] value,{{sfn|Buturovic|2016|p=114}} and [[Semantics|semantically]] incorrect and contradicting as it derives from the verb "to stand", while the chest-type to which it refers predominantly is laid down, while another sub-type of pillars and crosses is the one predominantly upright; this upright or standing sub-type does not amount even 5% of the overall number of stećci; in the original stećci inscriptions they are most often called as ''kami'' (meaning "stone" regardless of the form), thus some scholars proposed the term ''kamik'' (pl. ''kamici'') for all forms of headstones, while ''stećak'' would mean only the upright sub-type.{{sfn|Kužić|2001|p=271–273}} The term ''kamik'' is more close to the original meaning and sometime is used instead of ''stećak'' in professional literature.{{sfn|Lovrenović|2013|p=60}}

The stećci area or cemetery folk names show respect and admiration for their dimensions, age or representations: Divsko groblje (Giants’ cemetery), Mašete (big stones), Mramori/Mramorje (marble blocks), Grčko groblje (Greek cemetery), Tursko groblje (Turkish cemetery), Kaursko groblje ([[Giaour]]’s cemetery).{{sfn|Lovrenović|2013|p=59}}<ref name="Unesco2016"/>

==Characteristics==
===Definition===
[[File:Radimlja pobliz Stolce, nejvetsi nekropole stecku v BaH1.jpg|thumb|250px|Stećci at [[Radimlja]] necropolis.]]
They are characteristic for the territory of present-day [[Hercegovina]], central [[Bosnia (region)|Bosnia]], [[Podrinje]] and [[Dalmatia]] (especially South of river [[Cetina]]), and some minor parts of [[Montenegro]], [[Kosovo]] and Western [[Serbia]], [[Posavina]] and Northwestern Bosnia.{{sfn|Cebotarev|1996|p=321}}

Stećci are described as horizontal and vertical tombstones, made of stone, with a flat or gable-top surface, with or without a pedestal.{{sfn|Milošević|1991|p=6, 61}}{{sfn|Cebotarev|1996|p=321}} The common classification was established by Dmitrij Sergejevski in 1952, who divided them into recumbent stećci and standing stećci.{{sfn|Lovrenović|2013|p=62}} The systematization of stećci is not currently complete. According to [[Šefik Bešlagić]], there are seven main shapes: slab, chest, chest with pedestal, ridge/gable, ridge/gable with pedestal, pillar, and cross;{{sfn|Kužić|2001|p=271–273}} while according to Lovrenović, there are nine types in [[Radimlja]]: slab, slab with pedestal, chest, chest with pedestal, tall chest, tall chest with pedestal, sarcophagus (i.e. ridge/gable), sarcophagus with pedestal, cruciform.{{sfn|Lovrenović|2013|p=62}}

For instance, in Bosnia and Herzegovina, according to UNESCO, "about 40,000 chests, 13,000 slabs, 5,500 gabled tombstones, 2,500 pillars/obelisks, 300 cruciform tombstones and about 300 tombstones of indeterminate shape have been identified. Of these, more than 5,000 bear carved decorations".<ref name="UnescoBiH"/>

The chronology established by [[Marian Wenzel]] assumes they developed from the plate [[headstone]]s, the oldest one dating back to 1220 (the first were probably erected sometime in the mid-12th century<ref name="Unesco"/>), the monumental ones emerged somewhere around 1360, those with visual representations around 1435&ndash;1477, and that total production ended circa 1505.{{sfn|Milošević|1991|p=6}}{{sfn|Cebotarev|1996|p=322}} However, some consider that it lasted until the late 16th century, with rare examples that continued until the 18th century.{{sfn|Purgarić-Kužić|1995|p=244}} Stećci in the form of chest (''sanduk'') and ridge/saddle-roofed (''sljemenjak'') do not seem to have appeared before the middle or the end of the 14th century (1353-1477{{sfn|Lovrenović|2013|p=176}}), while the remaining two basic forms - the upright pillar (''stup'') and cross (''krstača'' / ''križina''), no earlier than mid-15th century. In the case of the latter, upright or standing forms could be influenced by the ''nišan'' - the upright monolithic stones on top of the Muslim (Turkish) graves, which had already emerged by the end of the 14th century in conquered parts of Macedonia and Serbia.{{sfn|Cebotarev|1996|p=321}}{{sfn|Lovrenović|2013|p=69–71}} This form is predominantly found in Serbia and Eastern Bosnia.{{sfn|Purgarić-Kužić|1995|p=244}}

The initial stage of their development, which included simple recumbent plates or slabs isn't specific for the region, but it is of broad West Mediterranean origin, and as such the term ''stećak'' (implying the chest and ridge form) is misleading for all tombstone forms. The slabs were typical for a kind of burial in the West Mediterranean world of the 14th and 15th centuries, which had a special method of production and ornamentation in the Balkans, customized according to the stonemasonry skills and microenvironment.{{sfn|Milošević|1991|p=6–7}}{{sfn|Mužić|2009|p=326}} The dated monuments indicate they were initially made by/for the feudal nobility, while later this tradition was embraced and adopted by the indigenous [[Vlachs in medieval Bosnia and Herzegovina|Vlachs]] who have almost exclusively built them from the mid-15th century on.{{sfn|Lovrenović|2013|p=72, 176}}{{sfn|Buturovic|2016|p=118}}

===Decorations===
{{quote box|width=18%|align=right|quote="I have for long lain here, and for much longer shall I lie"; "I was born into a great joy and I died into a great sorrow"; "I was nothing then, I am nothing now"; "You will be like I, and I can not be like you"; "May he who topples this stone be cursed" |source=— Some translated examples of inscriptions.{{sfn|Buturovic|2016|p=121}}{{sfn|Purgarić-Kužić|1995|p=249}}}}
A fraction of stećci (384{{sfn|Trako|2011|p=73}}) bear inscriptions, mostly in extinct [[Bosnian Cyrillic]], some in [[Glagolitic alphabet|Glagolitic]] and [[Latin alphabet|Latin]] script. The language has some archaic phrases, characterized by [[Serbo-Croatian#Division by jat reflex|Ikavian]] while toward the end by Ijekavian [[yat]] reflex.{{sfn|Purgarić-Kužić|1995|p=248}} The inscriptions can be roughly divided into those of: religious phrase, description of heroic death, information of the deceased, information of the deceased's relatives and circumstances of death, information with only personal name (sometime with smith-pupil name), moral (or religious) lesson.{{sfn|Lovrenović|2013|p=371}} The last are mostly brazen reminders of wisdom and mortality, relay a dread of death, more anxiety than peace.{{sfn|Buturovic|2016|p=121}}

The most remarkable feature is their decorative motifs roughly divided in six groups which complement each other: social symbols, religious symbols, images of posthumous [[Kolo (dance)|kolo]], figural images, clear ornaments, and unclassified motifs (mostly symbolic, geometrical, or damaged).{{sfn|Lovrenović|2013|p=369}} Many of them remain enigmatic to this day; [[spiral]]s, arcades, [[Rosette (design)|rosettes]], [[Vine|vine leaves and grapes]], [[lilium]], stars (often six-pointed) and [[Crescent|crescent Moon]]s are among the images that appear. Figural images include processions of [[deer]], [[horse]], dancing the kolo, [[hunting]], chivalric tournaments, and, most famously, the image of the [[man]] with his right hand raised, perhaps in a gesture of [[fealty]].{{sfn|Cebotarev|1996|p=322}}{{sfn|Lovrenović|2014|p=73–122}}

A series of visual representations on the tombstones can not be simplistically interpreted as real scenes from the life, and symbolic explanation is still considered by the scholarship.{{sfn|Purgarić-Kužić|1995|p=251}} The shield on the tombstones, usually with the crossbar, crescent and star, cannot be coat of arms, neither the lilium which is stylized is used in the heraldic sense. On one stećak is displayed tied lion and above him winged dragon. Already in 1979, historian Hadžijahić noted that the horsemen are not riding with [[rein]]s, yet (if are not hunting) their hands are free and pointed to the sky, implying possible cult significance.{{sfn|Mužić|2009|p=328}} In 1985, Maja Miletić noted the symbolic and religious character of the stećak scenes.{{sfn|Mužić|2009|p=329}} All the "life scenes" are considered to be part of ceremonial.{{sfn|Mužić|2009|p=334}} Several scholars concluded that the motifs, as well tradition of posthumous indigenous cult,{{sfn|Lovrenović|2013|p=61}} show the continuity of old Balkan pre-Christian symbolism from [[Prehistory of the Balkans|prehistoric]] time and the autochthonous Romanized [[Illyrians|Illyrian]] (i.e. [[Vlachs in medieval Bosnia and Herzegovina|Vlachian]]) tribes.{{sfn|Mužić|2009|p=329–335}} [[Alojz Benac]] noted that the displays of sole horse with snake, as well sole deer with bird, symbolize the soul of the deceased going to otherworld, which representations are resembling to those found on [[Iapydes]] artefacts.{{sfn|Mužić|2009|p=332–333}} The Illyrian god ''[[Paleo-Balkan mythology#Illyrian|Medaurus]]'' is described as riding on horseback and carrying a lance.{{sfn|Mužić|2009|p=333}}

[[File:Radimlje, bogumil nekropolisz sírkő 7.JPG|thumb|200px|The sacral motif of deer is considered to be of [[Paleo-Balkan mythology|Paleo-Balkan]] and pre-Christian origin.]]
Of the all animals deer is the most represented, and mostly is found on stećci in Herzegovina.{{sfn|Mužić|2009|p=332}} According to [[Dragoslav Srejović]], spread of Christianity didn't cause disappearance of old cult and belief in sacred deer.{{sfn|Mužić|2009|p=331}} Wenzel considered it lead the deceased to [[underworld]].{{sfn|Purgarić-Kužić|1995|p=251}} Historian [[Šefik Bešlagić]] synthesized the representations of deer: sometime accompanied by a bird (often on the back or horns), cross or lilium, frequently are shown series of deer or doe, as well with a bow and arrow, dog and hunter(s) with a spear or sword (often on a horse). It is displayed in hunting scenes, as well some kolo processions which are led by a man who is riding a deer.{{sfn|Mužić|2009|p=328–329}} There scenes where deers calmly approach the hunter, or deers with enormous size and sparse horns.{{sfn|Mužić|2009|p=329}} Most of the depictions of "deer hunting" are facing the [[West]], which had the symbolic meaning for death and otherworld. In the numerous hunting scenes in only one deer is wounded (the stećak has some anomalies), indicating unrealistic meaning. In the [[Roman art|Roman]] and [[Parthian art|Parthian]]-[[Sasanian art|Sasanian]] art hunted animals are mortally wounded, and deer is only one of many, while on stećci is the only hunted animal.{{sfn|Mužić|2009|p=336}}

[[File:Stećci, Risovac, Bosnia and Herzegoivna II.JPG|thumb|left|200px|Two stećci with motifs of [[Kolo (dance)|kolo]].]]
The motifs of ''kolo'' (in total 132{{sfn|Lovrenović|2014|p=91}}) procession along a deer, and its specific direction of dancing, although not always easily identifiable, show its a mortal dance compared to cheerful dance. From [[Iapydes]] urns, up to present day women in Bosnia and Herzegovina, and Montenegro, remorseful dances are played in the westward{{sfn|Purgarić-Kužić|1995|p=251}} direction toward sunset. In Eastern Bosnia and Herzegovina so-called ''Ljeljenovo kolo'',{{refn|group="nb"|See [[spring procession of Ljelje/Kraljice]] in Croatia with swords and flowers, similarly danced by [[Vlachs of Serbia|Vlachs]] east of [[Beograd]] at the day of [[Pentecost]].{{sfn|Mužić|2009|p=334}} The etymological and cultural relation of ''jelen'' (deer), ''Ljelja'' and ''Ljeljo'' which are children of [[Perun]], as well flower ''ljiljan'' (lilium) also called as ''perunika'' is still to be confirmed.{{sfn|Mužić|2009|p=335}} [[Ivo Pilar]] noted that the use of name ''Ljeljen'' for hills in toponymy of Herzegovina and Eastern Bosnia is common.{{sfn|Mužić|2009|p=331–332}}}} with ''ljeljen'' local name for ''jelen'' (deer) implying ''jelenovo kolo'', is danced by making the gate of the raised hand and ringleader of these gates tries to pull all kolo dancers through them until the kolo is entangled, after that, playing in the opposite direction, until the kolo is unraveled. Its origin is in mortuary ritual guiding the soul to another world and the meaning of renewal of life.{{sfn|Mužić|2009|p=334}}

{{multiple image
 | width = 120
 | footer = The [[Star and crescent|crescent moon and star(s)]] are a very common motif on the stećak tombstones.
 | image1 = Stećak u Baljvinama.jpg
 | image2 = Sarajevo Stecci 3.JPG
}}

The vast regional, but scarce (usually only one) in-graveyard distribution mostly in the center or some notable position of cross-type stećci (''križine''), and their almost exclusively ornament of the crescent Moon and stars, could indicate cemetery label for specific (pagan) religious affiliation. The symbolism of the Moon and stars (Sun), which are often found on them, could be traced to combination of pagan and Christian beliefs, {{sfn|Lovrenović|2014|p=80–81}} pix-pointed star represent [[Venus]] (in Slavic mithology called Danica) and with Moon could represent "astral marriage",{{sfn|Purgarić-Kužić|1995|p=250}} or even [[Mithraism]] which had old [[Mazdak]]ism belief that the dead body goes to the Moon and souls to the Sun,{{sfn|Milošević|1991|p=42}} while some considered a connection between astral simbols with the position of celestial bodies at the time of death of the deceased.{{sfn|Lovrenović|2014|p=81}}

===Schools===
They were carved by ''kovač'' / ''klesar'' (smith, mason; in the sense of Latin ''faber'', "master"{{sfn|Lovrenović|2013|p=369}}), while the inscriptions, probably as a template, were compiled by ''dijak'' / ''pisar'' (pupil, scribe). Until now are known 33 personal names of masons, among whom most notable is Grubač due to quality and being both a mason and scribe. He made four stećci in Boljuni and four stećci in Opličići near [[Stolac]].{{sfn|Lovrenović|2014|p=86}} The most notable scribe was Semorad who also worked around Stolac. It is considered that the masons studied the craft in Dalmatia and Ragusa, and from them those in hinterland.{{sfn|Purgarić-Kužić|1995|p=247}}

Stećci were mostly carved out of huge blocks, mostly of [[limestone]]. The vicinity of quarry was most significant for the cemetery location. Some of them weight more than 29 [[tonnes]], and it is supposed they were transported by horse or ox carriage while the heaviest with a combination of sledges and flat billets. They were placed directly above the pit, often in cardinal direction West-East, therefore so were the deceased. Seemingly it was related to the [[Sun path]] and was of importance that the dead watch the rising Sun.{{sfn|Purgarić-Kužić|1995|p=245}}

Stećci in Bosnia and Herzegovina can be roughly divided on two stonemasonry schools Herzegovian (sarcophagi with arcades, figurative scenes, a wealth of motifs) and East Bosnian (sarcophagi in the form of chalets, floral motives).{{sfn|Mužić|2009|p=327, 336}} The leading position had schools on the territory of Herzegovina, with center around [[Stolac]], in area of [[Trebinje]] and [[Bileća]], [[Gacko]] and [[Nevesinje]]. The fourth workshop was in the area of [[Konjic]], while the fifth around [[Široki Brijeg|Lištica]]. The stonemasons center in Western Bosnia was between [[Kupres]] and [[Duvno]], in Central Bosnia around [[Travnik]], while in Eastern Bosnia were four workshops, one between [[Kladanj]], [[Olovo]] and [[Ilijaš]], second around [[Zvornik]], third in [[Ludmer]], and fourth around [[Rogatica]].{{sfn|Lovrenović|2013|p=372}}

[[File:Stećak ploča.JPG|thumb|200px|A slab stećak at Cista Velika.]]
In Croatia supposedly were two workshops, one in Cista Velika, and second in Čepikuće.{{sfn|Purgarić-Kužić|1995|p=247}} Local characteristic of stećci in the territory around [[Cetina]] river in [[Croatia]] is their rare ornateness, of which only 8-10% have simple decoration.{{sfn|Milošević|1991|p=40}}{{sfn|Milošević|2013|p=91}} Those from upper Cetina are smaller and by type and style relate to those from Knin and [[Livno]], while those from mid Cetina are more monumental.{{sfn|Milošević|1991|p=61}} Specific plate stećci were found in village Bitelić which are decorated with identical geometric ornament, not found in [[Dalmatia]] nor in Bosnia and Herzegovina, however by the nature of ornament and surface treatment is considered possible connection with several monuments near Church of St. Peter in [[Nikšić]], [[Montenegro]].{{sfn|Milošević|1991|p=40}}{{sfn|Cebotarev|1996|p=323}}

In Montenegro one center could have existed around Nikšić, while second in [[Pljevlja]]. According to Bešlagić, in Serbia seemingly were no specific centers yet the masons arrived from Bosnia and Herzegovina.{{sfn|Purgarić-Kužić|1995|p=247}}

==Origin==
There are different and still inconclusive theories on their cultural-artistic, religious and ethnic affiliation.{{sfn|Milošević|1991|p=7}}{{sfn|Trako|2011|p=71–72, 73–74}} According to common thesis, especially represented by Bešlagić, stećci are an original Bosnian-Herzegovinian cultural-artistic medieval phenomenon.{{sfn|Zorić|1984|p=208}} Some scholars like [[Milovan Gavazzi]] (1978) examined a much broader context, and considered their connection to [[megalith]]ic tradition of the region and Eurasia from prehistoric and contemporary period.{{sfn|Zorić|1984|p=207–211}} Some scholars considered that the ''chest'' form could have been inspired by [[Romanesque architecture|Romanesque]] and [[Gothic architecture|Gothic houses]] from the coastal cities, while the ''ridge'' form by medieval Christian [[sarcophagus]] or local Bosnian wooden house.{{sfn|Purgarić-Kužić|1995|p=244}} It is established that they are mainly related to mountainous places which became deserted over a period of time because of migrations caused by new social events and [[Ottoman occupation of Bosnia and Herzegovina|Ottoman occupation]].{{sfn|Lovrenović|2013|p=42–43}}

===Religion===
Since the middle of the 19th century, specifically since the 1875 thesis by [[Arthur Evans]],{{sfn|Trako|2011|p=75}}{{sfn|Lovrenović|2013|p=33, 367}} many scholars including [[Alexander Soloviev (historian)|Alexander Soloviev]], Kosta Hörmann and [[Ćiro Truhelka]] have initially argued that they were related to the origin of the [[Bosnian Church]] i.e. [[Bogomilism|Bogomils]] or other [[Dualistic cosmology|dualist]] groups.{{sfn|Milošević|1991|p=7}}{{sfn|Cebotarev|1996|p=322}} Others have asserted that the church was actually founded by [[Franciscan|Franciscan monks]] from the [[Catholic Church]].{{sfn|Fine|2007|p=}} However, Benac noted that the stećci were not built in [[First Bulgarian Empire]], and that in Central Bosnia where were centers of [[Bosnian Kingdom|Kingdom of Bosnia]] and Bosnian Church is smaller concentration, as well higher number of stećci of poor design, but also older date.{{sfn|Mužić|2009|p=327}} The exclusive relation between stećci and Bogomils was propagated from the late 19th century due to political and ideological reasons, like by [[Béni Kállay]] and Austro-Hungarian authorities who promoted post-Ottoman and pan-Bosnian identity because since 1878 the territory was part of Austro-Hungarian administration,{{sfn|Purgarić-Kužić|1995|p=242}}<ref name="Textbook">{{cite book |author1=Ronelle Alexander |author2=Ellen Elias-Bursac |title=Bosnian, Croatian, Serbian, a Textbook: With Exercises and Basic Grammar |date=2010 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BziI02At36UC |publisher=University of Wisconsin Pres |page=270 |isbn=9780299236540}}</ref> rather than scientifical reasons.{{sfn|Kužić|2001|p=273}} Although was already questioned in the 1899 by Kosta Hörmann the first director of [[National Museum of Bosnia and Herzegovina]], for almost a century it was a predominant theory in international historiography.{{sfn|Lovrenović|2013|p=35, 367}}

Since the mid-20th century many scholars like [[Marian Wenzel]],{{sfn|Lovrenović|2013|p=368}} the world's once leading authority on the art and artifacts of medieval Bosnia and Herzegovina,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2002/mar/05/arts.guardianobituaries |work=The Guardian |location=London |title=Marian Wenzel | date=March 5, 2002 |accessdate=May 24, 2010 |first=Anthea |last=Brook}}</ref> concluded that the stećci tombstones were a common tradition amongst Catholic, Orthodox and Bosnian Church followers alike.{{sfn|Lovrenović|2013|p=38–43}}<ref name="WM"/> Wenzel's conclusion supported other historians' claims that they reflect a regional cultural phenomenon rather than belonging to a particular religious faith.<ref name="Textbook"/><ref>{{cite book |last=Fine |first=John V. A. |author-link=John Van Antwerp Fine, Jr. |title=The Late Medieval Balkans: A Critical Survey from the Late Twelfth Century to the Ottoman Conquest |year=1991 |publisher=University of Michigan Press |isbn=0-472-08149-7 |page=486}}</ref> Sometime the inscriptions/motifs do reveal the confessional affiliation of necropolis/deceased to one of the three Church organizations in medieval Bosnia and Zachlumia.{{sfn|Purgarić-Kužić|1995|p=253}}{{sfn|Lovrenović|2013|p=373}} This interconfessionality of stećci is one of their most remarkable features, and indicates high degree of [[Christianization]] of medieval Bosnian community.{{sfn|Lovrenović|2013|p=373}} However, it is considered that there is not enough basis to be perceived as exclusively Christian.{{sfn|Trako|2011|p=80}}

[[Christian Gottlob Wilke]] sought origins of the simbolic motifs in the old Mediterranean spirituali and religious concepts. Đuro Basler in the artistic expression saw some parallels in late [[Romanesque architecture|Romanesque]] art, while in simbolic motifs three components; pre-Christian, Christian and [[Manichaeism|Manichaean]] (i.e. Bogomil).{{sfn|Milošević|1991|p=7}} Bešlagić asserted that those who have raised and decorated them were not completely Christianized because they practiced the old custom of putting attachments with the dead, and many artefacts made of metals, textiles, ceramics and skin, coins, earrings of silver, gilded silver and solid gold have been found in graves beneath stećci.{{sfn|Mužić|2009|p=338}} The customs like placing coin in mouth ([[Charon's obol]]),{{sfn|Purgarić-Kužić|1995|p=245}} and placing drinking vessel near graves and heads, are from antique time.{{sfn|Mužić|2009|p=338}} Tomb pits were mostly used for one burial, but sometime were for two and more. Based on one stećak inscription in Montenegro, Bešlagić argued that there was a pre-Christian custom of re-burial, in which the bones were washed and returned to the pit.{{sfn|Purgarić-Kužić|1995|p=245–246}}

===Ethnic origin===
The ethnic identity of the stećci has not yet been fully clarified. Until now the most dominant, but still not fully accepted,{{sfn|Mužić|2009|p=327}} theory relates them with the autochthonous [[Vlachs in medieval Bosnia and Herzegovina|Vlach]] communities in the Balkan.{{sfn|Cebotarev|1996|p=322}}{{sfn|Kurtović|2013|p=2}} Opponents of this theory consider that their demographic number was too small, were profane and isolated, argue that the Vlachs did not built them from the fall of [[Western Roman Empire]], or that mythological symbols are related to Old Slavic rather than "Vlach" pagan beliefs.{{sfn|Purgarić-Kužić|1995|p=252}}

Bešlagić and others related them to formation of Bosnian Kingdom and especially Bogomils, however the shortage of this theory is in the fact Bosnian Kingdom existence was presumably too short for change in folk tradition, Bosnian Church existed later and ended sooner than stećci, Bosnian Church area of influence can not explain them in littoral and Serbian lands, other Bogomils did not built them, many necropolises are located around contemporary church ruins as well some stećci were secondarily embedded into churches and mosques,{{sfn|Lovrenović|2013|p=48}} and that the Bogomils did not respect the simbol of [[Christian cross|cross]] yet on the stećci it is very common.{{sfn|Purgarić-Kužić|1995|p=252}}

Some other scholars proposed unconvincing and rejected theories; [[Ivo Pilar]] (1918) ideologically argued Croatian origin of medieval Bosnia,{{sfn|Lovrenović|2013|p=37–38}} later [[Dominik Mandić]] considered them to be part of the ritual of burial by the pagan Croats from the [[Red Croatia]], Ante Škobalj similarly argued the Croatian theory,{{sfn|Purgarić-Kužić|1995|p=252}} Vaso Glušac ideologically argued Serbian-Orthodox origin of both Bosnian Church and stećci,{{sfn|Lovrenović|2013|p=37}} while Vladislav Skarić considered they have represented Old Slavic "eternal home", and that initially were built from wood.{{sfn|Milošević|1991|p=7}} [[Vladimir Ćorović]] pointed out that the "Old Slavs have not used monoliths or larger blocks of stone to make their apartments, let alone for the grave signs. Even the less for their writing or decorations".{{sfn|Mužić|2009|p=332}}

====Vlachs====
[[File:Bosnia Bogomil Tombstone 1901.jpg|thumb|250px|Broken stećak depicted by [[Hugo Charlemont]], 1901.]]
The autochthonous Vlachian theory was proposed by Bogumil Hrabak (1956) and Marian Wenzel (1962), and more recently was supported by the archeological and anthropological researches of skeleton remains from the graves under stećci.{{sfn|Milošević|1991|p=8}} However, the theory is much older and was first proposed by [[Arthur Evans]] in his work ''Antiquarian Researches in Illyricum'' (1883). While doing research with [[Felix von Luschan]] on stećak graves around [[Konavle]] found out that a large number of skulls weren't of Slavic origin yet similar to older Illyrian and [[Arbanasi people|Arbanasi]] tribes, as well noted that [[Dubrovnik]] memorials recorded those parts to be inhabited by the Vlachs until the 15th century.{{sfn|Mužić|2009|p=322}}

Hrabak was the first scholar to connect the historical documents and their relation to the persons mentioned on rare inscriptions on the stećci. In 1953 he concluded that the smith-stonemason Grubač from Boljun necropolis near [[Stolac]] built stećak of Bogavac Tarah Bol(j)unović not later than 1477, and that most of the monuments of Herzegovinian Vlachs, and not only Herzegovian and not only Vlachs,{{sfn|Buturovic|2016|p=118}} could be dated to the second half of the 15th century.{{sfn|Mužić|2009|p=322}} Wenzel in one of her studies researched sixteen stećci with similar dating and historically known persons. She noted the possibility that initially the stone monuments as such could have been introduced by the feudal nobility in the mid 14th century, which tradition was embraced by the Vlach tribes who introduced figural decoration.{{sfn|Mužić|2009|p=322}}{{sfn|Buturovic|2016|p=118}} The termination of the stećci production Wenzel related to the Ottoman invasion and new social circumstances, with the transition of Vlachs and near Slavs to Islam resulting with loss of tribal organization and characteristics of specific ethnic identity.{{sfn|Milošević|1991|p=8}}{{sfn|Cebotarev|1996|p=322}}

[[Sima Ćirković]] (1964) and [[Marko Vego]] (1973) argued that the emergence of the stećci among Vlachs coincides with their social-economical rise, confirmed in region of [[Zachlumia]] where is located the most well known necropolis of [[Radimlja]] related to the Vlachian family Miloradović-Stjepanović from genus Hrabreni.{{sfn|Lovrenović|2013|p=72}} Financial possibilities of ordering such expensive ways of burial among Vlachs are supported and confirmed in the historical documents, with an example of Vlach from Cetina, Ostoja Bogović, who in 1377 paid the cost of burial of Vlach Priboja Papalić for 40 [[Lira|libra]]. At the time burial in [[Split, Croatia|Split]] costed 4-8 libra, while for a sum of 40 libra could be bought family grave in the church of Franciscan order in [[Šibenik]].{{sfn|Milošević|1991|p=45}}{{sfn|Cebotarev|1996|p=323}}

Benac concluded that the distribution of the stećci in the lands right of the Cetina river coast in the parts of Dalmatian [[Zagora (Croatia)|Zagora]], while their absence in the lands left of the river (with graveyards along Early Middle Age churches), show these tombstones in those parts belonged to the Vlachian communities.{{sfn|Cebotarev|1996|p=321}} The triangle between [[Šibenik]], [[Trogir]] and [[Knin]], as well surroundings of [[Vrlika]] and [[Trilj]], which were the main centers of Vlachs, have the most number of stećci in Dalmatia.{{sfn|Milošević|2013|p=90}} In 1982, Benac noted that the highest concentration of them is in South Herzegovina (territory of [[Trebinje]], [[Bileća]], [[Ljubinj]] and [[Stolac]]), where was high concentration of Vlach population. Some of the stećci inscriptions (by anthroponyms) clearly relate them to some Vlachian chieftains; Tarah Boljunović from Boljun-Stolac, Vukosav Vlaćević from [[Vlahovići]]-Lubinje, Hrabreni and Miloradović in Radimlja-Stolac,{{sfn|Mužić|2009|p=323}} as well other distinctive members from Vlach groups like Bobani, Pliščići, Predojevići, [[Drobnjaci]]{{sfn|Kurtović|2015|p=316}} and to such chieftains belong finest monuments.{{sfn|Kurtović|2013|p=12}}

The occurrence of stećci in the Cetina county is related to the [[Nelipić noble family]] efforts to return economic and political power to whom was confiscated [[Knin]] in 1345 by king [[Louis I of Hungary]] in exchange for [[Sinj]] and Cetina county. They thrived with the support from the Vlachs, who for the service were rewarded with benefits and common [[Vlach law]].{{sfn|Milošević|1991|p=40}} After many conflicts and death of last noble Nelipić, then [[Ivan Frankopan]], Vlachs supported [[Stjepan Vukčić Kosača]].{{sfn|Milošević|1991|p=52–53}} The ridge stećci of ''Dalmatian type'' can be found only in regions of Dalmatia and Southwestern Bosnia, parts ruled by the [[Kosača noble family]]. It was in his interest to settle militant and well organized Vlachs in the most risky part of his realm, to defend from Talovac forces in Cetina and Venice forces in [[Republic of Poljica|Poljica]] and the coast. Thus Dalmatian type is found only West and South of Kosača capital [[Imotski]], and later also North after [[Ottoman conquest of Bosnia and Herzegovina|fall of Bosnia]].{{sfn|Milošević|1991|p=54}}

Anthropological research in 1982 on skeletons from 108 stećak graves (13-14th century) from Raška Gora near [[Mostar]], as well some from [[Grborezi]] near [[Livno]], shown homogeneity of the serials with clean [[Dinaric race|Dinaric]] anthropological type, without other admixtures, indicating non-Slavic origin, yet autochthonous Vlachian population.{{sfn|Mužić|2009|p=323}} The research of 11 skeletons from necropolis at Pavlovac near [[Prača (Pale-Prača)|Prača]], often attributed to the [[Pavlović noble family]], also shown clean Dinaric type, indicating Vlachian origin, although historical sources don't call Pavlovići as Vlachs.{{sfn|Mužić|2009|p=326}} The anthropological research in 1991 on the 40 skeletons from 28 burials (dated 1440-1450s) beneath stećci at plateau Poljanice near the village of [[Bisko]] showed that the vast majority of the population belonged to the autochthonous Dinaric type, concluding they were anthropologically of non-Slavic origin.{{sfn|Cebotarev|1996|p=322}} 21 skeleton belonged to child burial, while of 19 adult burials 13 belonged to males.{{sfn|Milošević|1991|p=35}} The [[quarry]] for stećci was found in the Northwestern part of the plateau, with one ridge as semi-finished work without any ornament.{{sfn|Milošević|1991|p=37}}

Archeologically, some Middle Age burials from Cetina county have local specifics by which Cetina county differs from other parts of Dalmatia. In the county the burials weren't done in the ground without additional stone architecture. Some scholars related this phenomenon to the specific ethnic identity, however due to still groundbreaking research for now is considered only regional and narrow local occurrence.{{sfn|Milošević|1991|p=35}}

==Legacy==
One of their enigma is the fact they were not mentioned in local and foreign medieval documents. Franciscan chronicles which recorded many unusual things, like Turkish cemetery, did not mention them.{{sfn|Lovrenović|2013|p=30–32}} Folk tradition preserved mythical perception full of superstitions and fantasy tales. It implies that occurred discontinuity of historical memory among all three ethnic groups, caused by ethnic migrations and religious conversions during the Ottoman occupation.{{sfn|Lovrenović|2013|p=31}} It is considered that the first [[Travel literature|itinerary]] mention of stećci is by [[Benedikt Kuripešić]] from 1530.{{sfn|Trako|2011|p=75}} [[Evliya Çelebi]] in 1626 described them as tombstone monuments of some unknown heroes.{{sfn|Trako|2011|p=75}} The oldest local author to mention them is [[Andrija Kačić Miošić]] in the mid-18th century.{{sfn|Lovrenović|2013|p=30}} [[Alberto Fortis]] in his work ''Travels into Dalmatia'' (1774) recorded them in [[Romanticist]] spirit of the time as described the tombstones in Cetina as warrior graves of the giants.{{sfn|Milošević|1991|p=39}}{{sfn|Trako|2011|p=75}} They also attracted attention by [[Aleksander Antoni Sapieha]], [[Ami Boué]], Otto Blau, [[John Gardner Wilkinson]] and Heinrich Sterneck.{{sfn|Lovrenović|2013|p=30}}

Since the second half of the 19th century, stećci are seen as a symbol of Bosnia and Herzegovina,<ref name="Textbook"/> being objects of South Slavic ideological ethno-national building myths and ownership,{{sfn|Buturovic|2016|p=115}} as well different opinions on their archaeological, artistic and historical interpretation.<ref name="Unesco2016"/> Although both Bosnian, Croatian and Serbian nationalism tried to annex them to their own culture, paradoxally, none of the three ethnic groups ([[Bosniaks]], [[Serbs of Bosnia and Herzegovina|Bosnian Serbs]] and [[Croats of Bosnia and Herzegovina|Bosnian Croats]]) in Bosnia and Herzegovina originally remember them in their collective consciousness, leaving them to nature or human destruction (which at least halved the number{{sfn|Lovrenović|2013|p=36}}), implying the annexation was based on constructions.{{sfn|Lovrenović|2013|p=28–38, 368}} Specifically, the thesis about the Bogomil origin of the stećci leaned along the theory of Bogomil origin of the Bosnian Muslims i.e. Bosniaks, which ideologisation and distortion of history was criticized by many scholars, and some like Wenzel stated that "thus stećci were given as a gift to Muslims, emphasizing their inheritance rights to the land and implying that the later Christians, comparatively, were the 'newcomers'".{{sfn|Lovrenović|2013|p=35}} The [[breakup of Yugoslavia]] and [[Bosnian War]] (1992–1995) caused a resurgence of Bogomil theory in public papers which sought historial-political legitimacy, ideologically aspired that Islamization was not only caused by Ottoman occupation yet it was an event dependent on Bogomils, and thus affirmed ethnical and confessional difference between Bogomil population and population of Catholic and Orthodox confession.{{sfn|Lovrenović|2013|p=43–46}} However, it did not make a significant influence on scientific thinking and comparative research.{{sfn|Lovrenović|2013|p=46–48}}

Europe's first public presentation of the gravestones is attributed to Russian immigrant and Yugoslav diplomat of Polish origin, [[Alexander Soloviev (historian)|Alexander Soloviev]] (1890-1971). He apparently wrote about them in the accompanying prospectus of Paris exhibition "Medieval art of the people of Yugoslavia" (1950).{{sfn|Trako|2011|p=75}} First regional public presentation was held in 2008 at [[Klovićevi Dvori Gallery]], and represented an example of encouraging public dialogue between four nations.{{sfn|Trako|2011|p=79}} They have influenced different art forms and were inspirational theme for sculptors, painters, poets, filmmakers, writers and photographers.<ref name="Unesco2016"/>

==Notable Stećci==
[[File:Grd3.jpg|thumb|250px|The inscription on stećak of [[Grdeša]] from the 12th century, considered the oldest one found.{{sfn|Lovrenović|2013|p=62}}]]

Stećci are commonly concentrated in groups: in cemeteries of individual families with few specimens, in cemeteries of whole families with approximately 30 up to 50 specimens, big necropolis of rural [[Opština|districts]] occasionally with several hundred specimens. Examples of family necropolis are those by [[Sanković noble family|Sanković]] in village Biskup near [[Konjic]], by Miloradović-Stjepanović (Hrabreni) in [[Radimlja]] near [[Stolac]], by [[Pavlović noble family|Pavlović]] near [[Sarajevo]], and by unknown family at Donja Zgošća near [[Kakanj]].{{sfn|Lovrenović|2013|p=372}} Today many Stećci are also displayed in the garden of the [[National Museum of Bosnia and Herzegovina]] in Sarajevo. The medieval [[Mramorje (Perućac)|Mramorje]] necropolis in [[Serbia]] is part of [[Monuments of Culture of Exceptional Importance (Serbia)|Monument of Culture of Exceptional Importance]] and contains large number of stećak tombs.<ref name="SANU" >{{CHS-SANU|Link=525|Name=Некропола стећака}}</ref> Some other notable or studied individual stećci:

* It is considered that the oldest known stećak is that of [[Grdeša]], a 12th-century [[župan]] of [[Trebinje]].{{sfn|Trako|2011|p=74}}{{sfn|Lovrenović|2013|p=63}}
* It is considered that the oldest known stećak with inscription is that of Marija, wife of priest Dabiživ, with inscribed number and presumed year-date 1231, from Vidoštak near Stolac.{{sfn|Trako|2011|p=74}}
* [[Vlatko Vuković|Vlatko Vuković Kosača]]'s grave lies marked near the village of Boljuni near [[Stolac]], Bosnia and Herzegovina, from the late 14th century. The inscription on the grave was written in [[Bosnian Cyrillic]] in [[Ikavian accent]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Šimić|first=Marinka|title=Jezik Boljunskih Natpisa|url=http://www.post.ba/download/boljuni.pdf|publisher=Staroslavenski institut}}</ref>
* The two ridge stećci which belonged to Bogumil Jerko Kustražić and his wife Vladna from the mid 15th century, in [[Cista Provo|Cista]] near [[Imotski]], and [[Split, Croatia]]{{sfn|Milošević|1991|p=54, 62}}
* The ridge stećak of Vlkoj Bogdanić (son of Radmil) who died in battle in the mid 15th century, made by mason Jurina, in [[Lovreć]], Croatia{{sfn|Milošević|1991|p=54, 62}}

